After a couple of days off due the choppy weather, we had some rust to shake off. As Brant said, we were the Bad News Bears of waterskiing this morning with some rookie level tumbles.

This morning's misadventures included:
- me almost nosediving off the swim platform, sweatshirt and all, when the boat accelerated a little faster than expected as I was checking the rope for knots
- we both had rough starts, bailing on our first attempt up. I somehow couldn't find the ski with my back leg??? I'm pretty sure I ended up doing the royal dancer yoga pose before crashing into the wake
- Brant's second set ended prematurely when his ski slipped out from under him when he doing nothing at all. When I told my dad (our driver) that he was down, he responded with "WHAT the HELL, he wasn't even skiing!"
- coming into the dock, Brant had a near miss when he decided at the absolute last second that he actually couldn't make the jump from boat to dock

Basically, it was the perfect way to end my vacation ‚ù§Ô∏è

Small victories. I had a really bad mental health day - I didn't get out of bed until after 4 pm. The ONLY two things I did were vote and run, but I did them.

This was by far the wettest, most miserable run I have done in a long time. I was soaked to the skin in less than 40 minutes and it never let up once. About 3 km from the end I stepped in several puddles that were deep enough to submerge my entire foot and it was AWFUL. First run since returning from injury that I thought "is this f@$#ing OVER yet??"

Gel Reviews

Gu Gel Chocolate Outrage: A surprising revelation! I didn't expect to like this, but the chocolate flavour was impressively robust; I was expecting sugary cheap Hershey's but it was closer to like a particularly creamy 65% dark chocolate ganache. This hid the "gel" flavour better than any other flavour I've had so far. Biggest complaint is the texture seemed thicker than most.
Overall: 4/5

Gu Gel Gingerade: Man, I had high hopes for this. I love ginger but this just didn't hit the spot. Unlike the chocolate, the ginger did NOT hide the gel flavour well at all. I was hoping for ginger ale, but it was more like Gravol non-drowsy ginger chews.
Overall: 2/5

Getting a couple extra km in since I didn't walk yesterday. After fighting a cramp for most of the run, I was feeling good at the end so I decided to log a proper attempt at Ryan's sprint... pretty happy with the result!

Two lessons learned today.

1. Dress warmer for speed work. By the time each recovery set was done I was FROZEN.

2. Charge my Garmin! It died on me during my run - thankfully just during the cooldown.

This speed work session went okay, but I'd love to hear any tips and tricks you have for intervals/speed work. I feel like I could have been more effective? I don't know haha.

Gel Review
Gu Gel Strawberry Banana: Okay, so. This is EXACTLY as advertised - it tastes like a strawberry banana smoothie or popsicle or something. It even had a somewhat banana-y texture. If I liked bananas, this would be an easy 4/5 or maybe higher, but as it is...
Overall: 2/5

Another nice tempo run. These are becoming my favourite workout and they're a nice way to see my progress. I was nervous about this one because it was my longest tempo yet but I felt strong the whole way through!

Gel Review
Gu Gel Chocolate Mint: We have our first winner folks! I guess this shouldn't have been a surprise since I love everything mint chocolate, but I honestly didn't expect to like this as much as I did. Similar to the chocolate outrage in terms of covering up the gel flavour, but the mint makes it just a little less cloying and that's enough to bump it up for me.
Overall: 5/5 ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê

Well this was a lot more enjoyable than last week's 16K in the pouring rain! A beautiful day for a run, I was happy to be out in the sunshine for a couple hours. Felt nice and comfortable the whole way.

Gel Reviews

Gu Gel Espresso Love: Every single person who hyped this flavour owes me an explanation. I'm not a coffee drinker and I was kind of dreading this flavour a bit because of that but it was honestly so... boring. The flavour was more Coffee Crisp than actual espresso (not a compliment) and it was pretty bland with a surprisingly prominent "gel" flavour. Texturally, it was a bit gritty. All in all, it wasn't TERRIBLE, but it certainly didn't live up to the hype. Someone explain to me why people like this so much because I DON'T GET IT.
Overall: 2/5

Gu Gel Campfire S'mores: This one, on the other hand, I get. I don't love marshmallows and I was afraid the whole thing would be ridiculously sweet but it actually wasn't bad. Not my favourite flavour (and again, not as robust as some of the other ones), but not bad. It's basically chocolate and marshmallow. In my perfect world, there'd be some Graham cracker flavour and maybe a little smoke but that's probably asking for too much haha
Overall: 3/5

Tomorrow's race plan: even splits (unusual for me) at an aggressive pace. Completely drain the tank and cross the finish line with nothing left. Find out how fast I can be. Nervous but excited!

Official time: 40:08

I'm so happy, my goal was 40 minutes and I wasn't even sure if it was attainable.

After bringing gear for all kinds of weather, conditions turned out near perfect with a light rain and very little wind.

My first race ever race running even splits and I hated doing it haha, but it's nice to know I can! Negative splits feel so much better both mentally and physically for me, but I'm so glad I got outside of my comfort zone.

Ways I kept myself distracted:
- counting how many women were ahead of me once we started to get passed by people who'd already hit the turnaround
- looking for familiar faces to say hi to
- playing "guess that shoe" with the runners ahead of me and rating people's footwear choices
- reading all the fun signs the course marshalls were holding
- trying to run the diagonals without cutting off anyone trying to overtake me

When I crossed finish line and saw the clock, I couldn't believe I'd done it. Had a couple tears as I was catching my breath, then when I found my dad (my cheer team for the day and lifelong runner who hasn't been able to run for the last 10 years) they really started in earnest. We both just hugged each other and cried for a bit. It was wonderful.

And now, on to the next one! BMO Half Marathon, here I come!

Happy birthday to me! üéÇ

One year ago, I was tackling the very first week of the Learn to Run program, incredibly grateful to be able to run for one minute at a time after four years of injury. My goal at that point was to run a 5K, something I wasn't sure would even be attainable without risking reinjury. I remember telling anyone who would listen that I looked like a lunatic because I was shuffling along on my run/walk program with this huge grin on my face because I was just so happy to finally be able to run again.

Today, I headed out for an easy 5K in the rain, as part of my training to run my first ever half marathon in something resembling a decent time. I'm sure I once again looked like a lunatic as I sang along to my headphones, danced and skipped in the rain, and realized halfway through that my face hurt from smiling. It's hard to believe how far I've come in a year, and man, I'm still so grateful to be able to run.
The runs are starting to feel good again! There's hope for me yet!

It's crazy how fast I'm getting back into the groove, I'm honestly surprised. 3 days ago, I ran an 8K with 15 minutes at race pace and nearly three up. Today's 10K with 50% more race pace felt challenging but comfortable! Let's hope this trend continues, since I'm now 20% of the way into my training for the half. ü§û
Slow and steady wins the race, right? Right?

Well this was one of the dumbest ideas I've had in a while. Longest run ever in the middle of the day with a substantial race pace section? I knew better but I did it anyway, and let me tell you, I suffered for it.

First of all, I had a couple moments where I got real concerned that heat exhaustion was going to be a problem. Should I have stopped and walked, found some shade, or maybe even called the run there? Probably. Did I? Of course not! I did slow down, but I told myself that I'd only call it off if I got disoriented or puked, which... yeah, not wise. We're going to blame this on being a stubborn idiot.

Secondly, that race pace section? Ha! I was too hot and too tired for anything more than a miserable shuffle. Still, a 6:01 pace on tired legs and while probably in the first stages of heat exhaustion is nothing to sneeze at, and I'm pretty happy with it. Bodes well for a sub 2 hour finish for my half.

Finally, I need to give a shoutout to the saintly but confused strangers who sprayed me with their garden hoses at my request. Legitimately probably kept me from a medical emergency and reinvigorated me both mentally and physically.

Let's not do this again any time soon, kay?

Last run before the big day!!

I survived!! Officially a half marathoner!

Of course Garmin was down, and of course it was one of the hottest days of the year, but no matter. I got out there and got it done.

The first 15K felt great. Relaxed, comfortable pace, chatting with my pacers Mark and Gurnek, putting time in the bank every kilometer.

And then... wow. I don't know if it was the heat, or just the pace and distance getting to me, but I definitely hit the wall. My pace dropped by close to 20 seconds and we all got a little nervous. I was able to pick it up again for a couple kms before it started to creep back up again around the 18 km mark...

...which coincidentally is also around the time I almost threw up, twice. I took in my last chew of the race and I guess I didn't actually chew it properly, because it got stuck in my throat a bit and I found my gag reflex trying very, very hard to do its thing.

At that point I was overheating, exhausted, and now this? Mark checked in to see if I was okay, and I waved him off; if I was going to vomit, I was going to do it on the move, because NOTHING was stopping me from crossing that finish line under 2 hours.

The run along North Fraser is a blur. I remember swearing a lot, crossing the road a couple times to find any shade I could, and constantly checking my watch to make sure I wasn't losing too much time since I felt like I was running through quicksand.

And then I came around the last corner into Foreshore Park and saw everyone standing and cheering for me and I was so overwhelmed with love and gratitude.

I might not have been able to run the real deal but I can't imagine a better way to finish my first half marathon than cheered in by so many amazing friends. Thank you all!

I could not have done it without all the wonderful friends and family who cheered me on and supported me in so many ways.

Extra thanks to: 
- My mom and dad for surprising me by driving home from Kamloops just to be here for my race.

- Mark and Gurnek for pacing me, keeping my spirits up, and taking all kinds of abuse, from me almost vomiting on them to some, err, choice words towards the finish.

- Mark again for not only pacing me but also being my sherpa/mobile aid station. He carried my water, nutrition, and more. I felt like Kipchoge as he handed me a gel on the run. True luxury!

- Michele and Katie for setting up an aid station so I could have my choice of water and nuun at the 5K and 15K mark, plus cookies and bananas at the finish line

- Amy for sending out the tracking link, for bringing pom poms and water to the half way point, and for buying and honest-to-god water gun to spray me down

- Michelle for making the best damn race signs of all time and stopping at multiple points along my route to cheer for me

- Pauline for having an absolutely HEAVENLY cup of ice water for me to dump all over myself with 4K to go

column3: Easy 8K + running in a mask for the first time
column5:
The air quality was shit, but I haven't run since Wednesday and I needed it for my mental health, so I decided to risk it.

We got new running masks at the store this week and I impulse bought this Buff one the day it arrived, so I figured I might as well test it out and see if it helped me not inhale QUITE as much smoke.

Pleased to report that running with a mask on is a lot less unpleasant than anticipated! It didn't chafe (which, as a sweaty human with sensitive skin, is a real concern) and I didn't need to adjust it or anything during the run.

I found it a little harder to breathe than normal and I *did* get my first side stitch in months, but we'll never know if that was a) because of the mask, b) because of the smoke, or c) because my pre-run fuel was a latte, corn chips, and jujubes lol

Also would not recommend wearing it with glasses/sunglasses. There's no nose wire and the filter pocket opens at the top, so it's pretty open up there. I could feel my warm breath shooting up my face constantly, and when I tried putting my sunglasses on, they fogged instantly.

Still, if I lived someplace where masks were mandatory when outside your home, I'd have no problem wearing it regularly to run. (And yes, it has a filter pocket, and yes, I did have a filter in. Still nice and breathable!)

Some bonus features:

- caught all my sweat so I wasn't constantly wiping my face with my also-sweaty arm

- protected me from the moth that would have flown RIGHT INTO MY MOUTH if I hadn't been wearing it

- running in a sports bra + mask on a two-lane winding country road made me feel like a badass action hero in a post-apocalyptic movie. üòÇ Just call me the next Charlize Theron!

Felt amazing to be able to push myself a little on this benchmark run, and only had the slightest tweak in my achilles at the very end, which subsided by the time I finished my cooldown walk. Officially running again and so, so happy about it!!! üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

Bit of an exciting one today! Someone tried to steal my shoes while I was doing my barefoot walk. Saw him rifling through my bag and said "excuse me, but that's mine" and he threw it at me and left in a hurry. Very glad I didn't have to walk home barefoot! üòÖ

Also checked out some of the damage from last night's windstorm - lots of branches down!
Got the last of the community day badges!
Beautiful day for a zen walk! No gloves, no toque, no frozen toes üòÇ
The Menu was way less scary than I expected, but very funny with just a little gore. Highly recommend!
Featuring the peak of running fashion: matching your outfit to the foliage üòÇ

column5: Too hot to get much of a walk in today, so went water running instead. Forgot how hard it is! üòÖ

5x1000 + 3x200

Let's call this one a learning experience. Didn't fuel properly last night. Didn't get up early enough to run before it got hot. Didn't take water with me.

My legs felt so heavy and the heat started to get to me about halfway through. Didn't quite hit the pace I wanted on the last 1000m repeat because I just couldn't get the legs to move.

But! I did wear my pretty pink carbon plate racing shoes for the first time so I could get a feel for them. And damn, I might not have looked good out there, but at least my shoes did! üòÇ

Also... not sure how strava thinks I covered 1.4k in 24 seconds. Because I assure you I did NOT.
